# CodeGuru / UpdateAI — Cursor Rules

## Project context
This is a web app that analyzes GitHub repos and generates .context.md files
to help vibe coders finish their AI-built apps. Read CONTEXT.md for the full
build plan, architecture, and step-by-step instructions.

## Code style
- Backend: Node.js, Express, CommonJS (require/module.exports) to match existing code
- Frontend: React with TypeScript, functional components, hooks
- Styling: Tailwind CSS
- Keep files small and focused — one service/component per file
- Use async/await everywhere, no callbacks
- Error handling: always try/catch async operations, return meaningful errors

## Existing code to reuse
- `packages/auth/` — Supabase auth. Import as `@codeguru/auth`. Don't modify it.
- `packages/github/` — GitHub API wrapper (originally migrated from the legacy code-reviewer prototype, then extended). `app/server/services/github.js` is a one-line re-export shim.
- `packages/sse/` — SSE helper (originally migrated from the legacy code-reviewer prototype). `app/server/lib/sse.js` is a one-line re-export shim.

## Legacy code
The original `_archived/{code-reviewer,codebase-analyzer,fastapi-project}` and
`code-visualizer-mvp/{workspace-app,workspace-prototype,knowledge-graph-extension}`
directories have been removed from main. They live on the `archive/legacy-snapshot`
git branch for reference only — do NOT copy code from them or re-introduce them
into the working tree. The active app lives entirely under `app/` and `packages/`.

## When generating code
- Always check CONTEXT.md for the expected file structure before creating files
- Follow the build order in CONTEXT.md — don't skip ahead
- When building analyzer.js, read REAL files from the repo via GitHub API
- When building context-generator.js, use Claude API with streaming
- Every API endpoint should handle errors and return useful error messages
- Frontend components should show loading, error, and empty states

## .context.md format
When generating .context.md file content (either in the app or as examples):
- Use ## headings for sections: owner, purpose, constraints, decisions, ai-log, dependencies, status
- Keep language clear and readable by non-engineers
- Constraints should be specific and actionable
- Decisions should include rationale and who/when

## Don't
- Don't restore the `_archived/` or `code-visualizer-mvp/{workspace-app,workspace-prototype,knowledge-graph-extension}` directories — they live on `archive/legacy-snapshot` and are not part of the live app.
- Don't build the Chrome extension yet
- Don't add authentication to the analyze endpoint — it should work without login
- Don't try to clone repos — use GitHub API to read files
- Don't read every file in a repo — be selective (max ~30 key files)
- Don't generate fake/guessed analysis — read real files
